ocr.line: ὴρ ἀλλ ῶήσαι καρπεπρα τετιλμεν
ocr.sentence: ὴρ ἀλλ ῶήσαι καρπεπρα τετιλμεν ἀλλ εήσιθως οματειρσος ηδητα τεμμε εμελλαφαέρειν, χη τρἀπερεἐσηρετο θενν φρασον πρτισοταις ἀρχήστρι ταιεενεκ τουπαις αὐτος ότεισερχομ αὶπαις ἀκολουθεδεύρότάσκευηφ πισγες ουτος χι που ου δηνποι επησε παιζων τρακλεα σηεαςε μοα φλυτρήσης ἔχωνω ξανθια ἀλλραμένος παλινοισειςταστρωμλς κἀντιδέστιν οὐ δη που μαφελεα ταιανοη α δω κας αὐτος διςοχτα χἀλλὴἐπο καταθητοδξμλξαν ταυτερ μεντύρδι τοῖς θεοῖσιν επιρεπω δις ποιοις θεο ώδὲ προς δοκήήσαι σκκἀνοητ ἐκεν ὶδουλος ὢν κδνητος ἀλκμην ευ ξανλμελει καλί εχαὐτ ισυς γοτο πό χου δεήθείης αειρεος δλοι Ταὶ ταυταμι πρ ανδρος εστινουν εχον αφεν

groundtruth.line: ἡβυλλιῶσαι κἄρτι παρατετιλμέναι
groundtruth.sentence: ἡβυλλιῶσαι κἄρτι παρατετιλμέναι ἀλλ εἴσιθ ὡς ὁ μάγειρος ἤδη τὰ τεμάχη ἔμελλ ἀφαιρεῖν χἠ τράπεζ εἰσῄρετο ἴθι νυν φράσον πρώτιστα ταῖς ὀρχηστρίσιν ταῖς ἔνδον οὔσαις αὐτὸς ὅτι εἰσέρχομαι ὁ παῖς ἀκολούθει δεῦρο τὰ σκεύη φέρων ἐπίσχες οὗτος οὔ τί που σπουδὴν ποεῖ ὁτιή σε παίζων Ἡρακλέα νεσκεύασα οὐ μὴ φλυαρήσεις ἔχων ὦ Ξανθία ἀλλ ἀράμενος οἴσεις πάλιν τὰ στρώματα τί δ ἐστίν οὔ τί πού μ ἀφελέσθαι διανοεῖ ἅδωκας αὐτός οὐ τάχ ἀλλ ἤδη ποιῶ κατάθου τὸ δέρμα ταῦτ ἐγὼ μαρτύρομαι καὶ τοῖς θεοῖσιν ἐπιτρέπω ποίοις θεοῖς τὸ δὲ προσδοκῆσαί σ οὐκ ἀνόητον καὶ κενὸν ὡς δοῦλος ὢν καὶ θνητὸς Ἁλκμήνης ἔσει ἀμέλει καλῶς ἔχ᾽ αὔτ ἴσως γάρ τοί ποτε ἐμοῦ δεηθείης ἄν εἰ θεὸς θέλοι ταῦτα μὲν πρὸς ἀνδρός ἐστι νοῦν ἔχοντος καὶ φρένας

groundtruth.line: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους
groundtruth.sentence: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια της ρεβεκκας εδιδαχθημεν συμβολον του αγαθα μελλειν αυτη διδαγματα περι της εν τοις νοη τοις αληθειας εν τω οικω του αβρααμ γενο μενη παραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχου κατειληφαμεν πρωτον μεν εκ του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα χθηναι παρα του ιακωβ τας γυναικας περι ελεσθαι αυτα των θεων των αλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιου οντος εκ της ειδωλολατρειας και της των ενωτιων χρησεως προς το ανελθειν εις τον οικον κυ βεθηλ γαρ οικος θυ ερμηνευεται επειτα εν τη εξοδω καταστασιασθεις υπο του λαου ο ααρων εις το ποιησαι ειδωλον ως επιτηδειαν υλην εις κατασκευην των απηγο ρευμενων τα ενωτια εξελεξατο περιειλα ντο γαρ πας ο λαος φησι τα ενωτια τα χρυσα τα εν τοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς αα ρων και επλασεν αυτα μοσχον χωνευτον αλ λα και γεδεων εκ των σκυλων των ισμαηλητι κων λαβων τα ενωτια παρα του λαου εποιη σεν αυτα εις εφουδ και εστησεν αυτο εν τη πολει και εξεπορνευσαν πας ιηλ οπισω αυτου εκει και εγενετο τω γεδεων και τω οικω αυτου εις σκανδαλον

(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.line: ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια
ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

groundtruth.line: επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια
groundtruth.sentence: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια της ρεβεκκας εδιδαχθημεν συμβολον του αγαθα μελλειν αυτη διδαγματα περι της εν τοις νοη τοις αληθειας εν τω οικω του αβρααμ γενο μενη παραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχου κατειληφαμεν πρωτον μεν εκ του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα χθηναι παρα του ιακωβ τας γυναικας περι ελεσθαι αυτα των θεων των αλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιου οντος εκ της ειδωλολατρειας και της των ενωτιων χρησεως προς το ανελθειν εις τον οικον κυ βεθηλ γαρ οικος θυ ερμηνευεται επειτα εν τη εξοδω καταστασιασθεις υπο του λαου ο ααρων εις το ποιησαι ειδωλον ως επιτηδειαν υλην εις κατασκευην των απηγο ρευμενων τα ενωτια εξελεξατο περιειλα ντο γαρ πας ο λαος φησι τα ενωτια τα χρυσα τα εν τοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς αα ρων και επλασεν αυτα μοσχον χωνευτον αλ λα και γεδεων εκ των σκυλων των ισμαηλητι κων λαβων τα ενωτια παρα του λαου εποιη σεν αυτα εις εφουδ και εστησεν αυτο εν τη πολει και εξεπορνευσαν πας ιηλ οπισω αυτου εκει και εγενετο τω γεδεων και τω οικω αυτου εις σκανδαλον

prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.line: ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο
ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

groundtruth.sentence: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια της ρεβεκκας εδιδαχθημεν συμβολον του αγαθα μελλειν αυτη διδαγματα περι της εν τοις νοη τοις αληθειας εν τω οικω του αβρααμ γενο μενη παραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχου κατειληφαμεν πρωτον μεν εκ του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα χθηναι παρα του ιακωβ τας γυναικας περι ελεσθαι αυτα των θεων των αλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιου οντος εκ της ειδωλολατρειας και της των ενωτιων χρησεως προς το ανελθειν εις τον οικον κυ βεθηλ γαρ οικος θυ ερμηνευεται επειτα εν τη εξοδω καταστασιασθεις υπο του λαου ο ααρων εις το ποιησαι ειδωλον ως επιτηδειαν υλην εις κατασκευην των απηγο ρευμενων τα ενωτια εξελεξατο περιειλα ντο γαρ πας ο λαος φησι τα ενωτια τα χρυσα τα εν τοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς αα ρων και επλασεν αυτα μοσχον χωνευτον αλ λα και γεδεων εκ των σκυλων των ισμαηλητι κων λαβων τα ενωτια παρα του λαου εποιη σεν αυτα εις εφουδ και εστησεν αυτο εν τη πολει και εξεπορνευσαν πας ιηλ οπισω αυτου εκει και εγενετο τω γεδεων και τω οικω αυτου εις σκανδαλον

prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.line: του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα
ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

groundtruth.line: του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα
groundtruth.sentence: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια της ρεβεκκας εδιδαχθημεν συμβολον του αγαθα μελλειν αυτη διδαγματα περι της εν τοις νοη τοις αληθειας εν τω οικω του αβρααμ γενο μενη παραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχου κατειληφαμεν πρωτον μεν εκ του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα χθηναι παρα του ιακωβ τας γυναικας περι ελεσθαι αυτα των θεων των αλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιου οντος εκ της ειδωλολατρειας και της των ενωτιων χρησεως προς το ανελθειν εις τον οικον κυ βεθηλ γαρ οικος θυ ερμηνευεται επειτα εν τη εξοδω καταστασιασθεις υπο του λαου ο ααρων εις το ποιησαι ειδωλον ως επιτηδειαν υλην εις κατασκευην των απηγο ρευμενων τα ενωτια εξελεξατο περιειλα ντο γαρ πας ο λαος φησι τα ενωτια τα χρυσα τα εν τοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς αα ρων και επλασεν αυτα μοσχον χωνευτον αλ λα και γεδεων εκ των σκυλων των ισμαηλητι κων λαβων τα ενωτια παρα του λαου εποιη σεν αυτα εις εφουδ και εστησεν αυτο εν τη πολει και εξεπορνευσαν πας ιηλ οπισω αυτου εκει και εγενετο τω γεδεων και τω οικω αυτου εις σκανδαλον

prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.

I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)

This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.line: όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο
ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

groundtruth.sentence: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια της ρεβεκκας εδιδαχθημεν συμβολον του αγαθα μελλειν αυτη διδαγματα περι της εν τοις νοη τοις αληθειας εν τω οικω του αβρααμ γενο μενη παραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχου κατειληφαμεν πρωτον μεν εκ του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα χθηναι παρα του ιακωβ τας γυναικας περι ελεσθαι αυτα των θεων των αλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιου οντος εκ της ειδωλολατρειας και της των ενωτιων χρησεως προς το ανελθειν εις τον οικον κυ βεθηλ γαρ οικος θυ ερμηνευεται επειτα εν τη εξοδω καταστασιασθεις υπο του λαου ο ααρων εις το ποιησαι ειδωλον ως επιτηδειαν υλην εις κατασκευην των απηγο ρευμενων τα ενωτια εξελεξατο περιειλα ντο γαρ πας ο λαος φησι τα ενωτια τα χρυσα τα εν τοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς αα ρων και επλασεν αυτα μοσχον χωνευτον αλ λα και γεδεων εκ των σκυλων των ισμαηλητι κων λαβων τα ενωτια παρα του λαου εποιη σεν αυτα εις εφουδ και εστησεν αυτο εν τη πολει και εξεπορνευσαν πας ιηλ οπισω αυτου εκει και εγενετο τω γεδεων και τω οικω αυτου εις σκανδαλον

τα τε δε μεταμελλεντες καθιζερον πεδην καλλιφων
δρον διοτρητιχον αναμενου φρενων χορον
δεκατισμενον αρμυρος ων δαιιν εχουσιν
• The play begins with an accompanying lament from a Cretan woman (Polyxena, daughter of high king Priam).
• The Dioscuri (Gemini) are mentioned in a lament. Otherwise the description of the sky resembles most the constellation of Orion, whose stars are visible on Crete the 11th-14th of November, the night in which the play was performed. The Dioscuri stood next to Orion, i.e. on the other side of the sky from his mourning.

《ΗΑΝΙΒΑΙΟΣ∆ΗΜΑ∆ΟΡΑΣ “Ἡ ΖΩΗ ΤΗΣ Ἑξηκονταετηρίδος” (ΙΩΝ)》 APPENDIX: Liber medicarum Alexandrinorum sive de medicinis cognitis et inventis
prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

I ZOPYRUS AEgyPTus, of not more than (several names ) years, a grammarian by profession, and a follower of the holy Archbishop Cyril of blessed memory, give and bequeath all my fortunes to my father who brought me up so far, and to his heirs. ZOPYRUS AEGYPTIUS, the best of men! [...]

And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. ocr.line: ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη
ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

groundtruth.sentence: φυρα και τα ενωτια και τους δακτυλιους επαινετην μεν χρησιν ενωτιων εν τη μνηστεια της ρεβεκκας εδιδαχθημεν συμβολον του αγαθα μελλειν αυτη διδαγματα περι της εν τοις νοη τοις αληθειας εν τω οικω του αβρααμ γενο μενη παραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχου κατειληφαμεν πρωτον μεν εκ του οτε αναβαινειν εμελλον εις βεθηλ προστα χθηναι παρα του ιακωβ τας γυναικας περι ελεσθαι αυτα των θεων των αλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιου οντος εκ της ειδωλολατρειας και της των ενωτιων χρησεως προς το ανελθειν εις τον οικον κυ βεθηλ γαρ οικος θυ ερμηνευεται επειτα εν τη εξοδω καταστασιασθεις υπο του λαου ο ααρων εις το ποιησαι ειδωλον ως επιτηδειαν υλην εις κατασκευην των απηγο ρευμενων τα ενωτια εξελεξατο περιειλα ντο γαρ πας ο λαος φησι τα ενωτια τα χρυσα τα εν τοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς αα ρων και επλασεν αυτα μοσχον χωνευτον αλ λα και γεδεων εκ των σκυλων των ισμαηλητι κων λαβων τα ενωτια παρα του λαου εποιη σεν αυτα εις εφουδ και εστησεν αυτο εν τη πολει και εξεπορνευσαν πας ιηλ οπισω αυτου εκει και εγενετο τω γεδεων και τω οικω αυτου εις σκανδαλον

prediction.sentence:
(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

(3) "ὁ οὐκ εὔξαστος εἷς ἄριδι λαχόν, φῶ τοῦτο λαχόν, κύπα" Readers often quote this verse and its "corrected text" and say something to the effect of Διόνυσος does not address one specifically with ὧδε , but οὐδέ are here and there in the declamation and therefore one should not understand Διόνυσος to be summoning a specific person. And this they say to remove the idea that there is an invitation of one in particular.   Note it is other times there and not in verse 6 εἰμί, οὐδέντο διισμῳκας when he doesn't specifically address a person. Another argument for the "invitation" theory is that what the child is told, as J. Harrison finds, is actually true of Agraiōn the female prostitute, who provides for him, or Leah to whom he refers to she is his mother, or Patrokos, whom he says is male & Aphrodite's altar meaning bedfellow.   Some will say that these examples do not exclusively speak of a ritual to Aphrodite because to describe a ritual does not make it a ritual. Yet, because it says he is mother or because a female is the mother it cannot be a ritual of Aphrodite and therefore not a pederastic love.   They go further and say there is nothing in the development of the narrative indicating that it is a ritual of Aphrodite, which is further contradicted by the sexual language uttered by Διόνυσος and that use of K 310 .   But, as W. H. Segal asks:   "Who is the prophecy for? An uninstructed outsider could hardly have been led through the pericope from 'my child who is to be born a girl' to the end of the story, with a list of suitors' names memorized in line 3 and internal explications to individuals in lines 8–9, 14–16, 18 and 23. It would have made more sense to use a conspicuously marked line as the division between what is said to me and what is said to others. (p.83)   
There is one to whom it is specifically delivered and that is the groom. His name is Theoklymenos (future Zeus). The announcement is delivered to Theoklymenos, it says 23 αὐτὸνπροςτεκναῖκα, αὐτὸς ἔλθε γαῖα μητί ἐγγύς; The explicit and intrinsic message in the line says he is summoned, expectant for his coming and his naming.
With respect to the ἀλλὰ καί .   Again, I go to G. Kroeger for help who says that the "desire for ἀλλά καί must not be explained as a free-and-easy device to include everybody. Williams' suggestion about 'elegant variations of metre' seems somewhat far-fetched and too easy an idea. I would suggest that in a poetic libretto, ἀλλά (Lines 4 & 5), ἀλλὰ καί (Lines 9, 11, & 17) and δῆλον (line 25) are the 'variable crescendos audivit' that the eighteenth-century poet does with a greater sense of autonomy." (p.98)
Furthermore, as I pointed out in Reading Praxilla and Kollias' Τῶνγυριόδων it is as if Διόνυσος says something and then says to be delivered to παιδίοις . This is different from the ἔγωγε you at the beginning of the text. It means "these ones here:" παιδίοις ἧν τοΰτομεναις .   For, the instructions to Theoklymenos the groom are to be delivered specifically to those [παιδίοις] to those "here" [ παιδίοις ἧν] but it does not exclude others.

ocr.line: κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο
ocr.sentence: φυρα, καὶ τάξ μωτικαι τος ακτλίες ὲπαιν ετὴν μενχρήησιμ ενωτιων εντη μνηστεια τησρθεμεν κας εδιδαχθημεν δμβολος τοῦ γαθά μολλειν αὐτη διδειγματα περιτῆς ἐν τοῖς νο ηκτοις αληθείας ἐντῷοικω του ἀβρααμγενο μεν ηπαραδοθησεσθαι κατηγορουμενα δε αυ τα πολλαχουκατειληφαμεν πρω το ύμεν εκ του ὁ τε αναβαινεια εμευλλος εἰσμεθηλ προστα λοκναι παρα του ιακωρτας γναικασπερι ἐλεσθαι αυτα των θεπντῶν ἀλλοτριων ως εμ ποδιουον τος εκτῆς ἐιδωλολατροίας καιτ των ἐνωτιων χρήσεως προςτο ανελθειω ἐις τοοικοήκύ κεθηλγαροιμυθυερηνευεται επειτα εντηδοδωκατα στασίασθεις υποτου λαουὁααρῶν ἐις τοποισαι ειδωλοη ς όπι τηδειαν χην εισκατασκευην των απηγο ρευμένῶν τα ενώτια εξελεξατο περιειλο τὸ γὰρ πας ολαος φησι τα ενωτια ταχρυσα τα εντοις ωσιν αυτων και ηνεγκαν προς ἀα ρων καὶ ὅπλασαν αὐταμος χοηχων εὐτὸν ἀλλ λακαιγεδεων εκτῶν σκύλωντων ισμαρχεητι ψξωνλαυων τα ενωτια παρα του λαουεποιη σεν αὐτα εισεφουι καὶ εστηεν αυτς ἐντη πολει καὶ ὅξεπορνευσανπας ιἡλοπισω αυτοῦ ἐκεῖι κεγενετοτωγεδων κα τῷοικῷ αυτοῦ εισσκανδολο

των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).
 τὸ δὲ λόγιον προστρέχει τοῦτονκαὶ τὰ
τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.
ZEC 9:9 (NIV)  Then those who live in the towns of Judah will go out and make firepits in the
cities of Judah and places around Jerusalem, from the Geba (City of Hope) to the
Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

prediction.sentence:
των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).
 τὸ δὲ λόγιον προστρέχει τοῦτονκαὶ τὰ
τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.
ZEC 9:9 (NIV)  Then those who live in the towns of Judah will go out and make firepits in the
cities of Judah and places around Jerusalem, from the Geba (City of Hope) to the
Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

PRAYER TO JOSHUA:

Every year on Christmas, the Archbishop of Athens visits the Cave of The Apocalypse. His Excellency, the Metropolitan of Euboea, Nikiforos graciously remembers students who are past the age of 3rd grade. Once you reach the age of 6th grade (5th for those past compulsory education), students have to visit the cave to both experience its mys­terious but

1. Let the Bateren not despise the works of the ancients ; let them not be contentious, nor self-willed, nor impatient: Let them be submissive to all, beneficent to all, compassionate to all, but not ready to entertain the advice of all.
2. Let them know there are two kinds of magic; that of good spirits and of evil ones,--the former is according to nature, is for the welfare of man, good, kind, and accords with order.
3. The other is distant from it, seems powerful and formidable, but is altogether passive and obnoxious to an overruling Providence, for it has not the goodness of the other. It is therefore, of little estimation with good men, and of great dread.

των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).
 τὸ δὲ λόγιον προστρέχει τοῦτονκαὶ τὰ
τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.
ZEC 9:9 (NIV)  Then those who live in the towns of Judah will go out and make firepits in the
cities of Judah and places around Jerusalem, from the Geba (City of Hope) to the
Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

PRAYER TO JOSHUA:

Every year on Christmas, the Archbishop of Athens visits the Cave of The Apocalypse. His Excellency, the Metropolitan of Euboea, Nikiforos graciously remembers students who are past the age of 3rd grade. Once you reach the age of 6th grade (5th for those past compulsory education), students have to visit the cave to both experience its mys­terious but

prediction.sentence:
των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).
 τὸ δὲ λόγιον προστρέχει τοῦτονκαὶ τὰ
τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.
ZEC 9:9 (NIV)  Then those who live in the towns of Judah will go out and make firepits in the
cities of Judah and places around Jerusalem, from the Geba (City of Hope) to the
Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

PRAYER TO JOSHUA:

Every year on Christmas, the Archbishop of Athens visits the Cave of The Apocalypse. His Excellency, the Metropolitan of Euboea, Nikiforos graciously remembers students who are past the age of 3rd grade. Once you reach the age of 6th grade (5th for those past compulsory education), students have to visit the cave to both experience its mys­terious but

των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).
 τὸ δὲ λόγιον προστρέχει τοῦτονκαὶ τὰ
τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.
ZEC 9:9 (NIV)  Then those who live in the towns of Judah will go out and make firepits in the
cities of Judah and places around Jerusalem, from the Geba (City of Hope) to the
Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

PRAYER TO JOSHUA:

Every year on Christmas, the Archbishop of Athens visits the Cave of The Apocalypse. His Excellency, the Metropolitan of Euboea, Nikiforos graciously remembers students who are past the age of 3rd grade. Once you reach the age of 6th grade (5th for those past compulsory education), students have to visit the cave to both experience its mys­terious but

των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).

τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.

Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

των γαρ Θεὸν νενοὑήκεις και τῆς ὁδοῦ Κυρίου ὁδῷ ζητω
τὸν Ἰησοῦν· οὐ διήνεγκε γάρ ἐνώπι σου, ἀλλ ἵλαι, σέ).
 τὸ δὲ λόγιον προστρέχει τοῦτονκαὶ τὰ
τοῦ προφήτου Ἔκραυγα σὲ Χριστέ! Ἰδού καὶ ἐνέπαισας.
Τὴν πὰρκαν τῆς κληρονομιᾶς πεπλάνησαι, καί σε ἐλθεῖν εἰς ἐμὲ δικαίως.
A literal translation:

For you have consorted with angels and embraced the way of the Lord,
Jesus (Joshua) the son of Mary, so that He grants you eternal life,
in the hereafter, in the Kingdom of Heaven. For no pious man shall enter into it
unless he is purified on both sides, more than Phineas among the sons of Israel.
This Cave shall be an ark, and those who preserve their purity shall survivors.
They shall lie in it for three and half years until salvation comes to its own again,
as had been foretold by our Holy Fathers; and they tell us that we will bring forth
sons, even worthy of eternal splendor. For you will be the great Covenant,
and the mouth of prophecies, and the first Prophet in them. If all said (it) to me, I
would still be a confounded and slumberer. Time will be full and his number shall be complete,
and the word of salvation, Jesus Christ.
And I said to the young man, "So now you have the angel, and the Preacher of God,"
and he replied to me, "I also heard him call Him the Mercy God, but listen now to
this statement, 'Anyone who created himself in the flesh prepare his tomb, and,
stumbling into sin, wail and do not let him be a false martyr. He will avenge you,
his name invoked in all prayers at every altar. Do not fear persecution, do not cringe
and give up the faith, for the kingdom of Ages is yours now. He is prepared a reward,
and it is just for you to take the bow out of its case. Do not grieve of your lack (of Paradise)'.
And I asked him, 'How will I be able to get him,' (the Prophet), and he replied to me, 'Reveal unto Aaron (me), and call for me. And if thy faith is true and
thou be a pure one, enter into the grace of my good will, and I will heal you with the blessing
of the Spirit, and I will go before you into the east; take my hand and I will reveal you where
the Lord is, and don't reject this opportunity to see the one who declares that he was wronged by your sins,
and that he will avenge you. "(Joshua 5:5  NIV translation.
ZEC 9:9 (NIV)  Then those who live in the towns of Judah will go out and make firepits in the
cities of Judah and places around Jerusalem, from the Geba (City of Hope) to the
Dalmanutha (The Fountain of Justice), and on the Mount of Olives, as far as the
threshold of the temple.

PRAYER TO JOSHUA:

His Excellency, the Metropolitan of Euboea, Nikiforos graciously remembers students who are past the age of 3rd grade. Once you reach the age of 6th grade (5th for those past compulsory education), students have to visit the cave to both experience its mys­terious but
